## STATE MANAGEMENT

### Choose the Right Tool

| Data type | Tool |
|---|---|
| Server / async data | React Query |
| Form data | React Hook Form |
| Global UI state (modals, theme) | Zustand |
| Local component state | `useState` / `useReducer` |
| Derived values | Compute inline, no extra state |

### Never Store Derived State

```tsx
// ‚ùå Derived state = bugs
const [fullName, setFullName] = useState(`${firstName} ${lastName}`)

// ‚úÖ Compute it
const fullName = `${firstName} ${lastName}`
```

### Colocate State
Keep state as close to where it's used as possible. Only lift state when genuinely shared.

### Avoid useEffect for Data Fetching
Use React Query. Every raw `useEffect` for fetching is a bug waiting to happen (race conditions, missing cleanup, no caching).

```tsx
// ‚ùå Raw effect fetching
useEffect(() => {
  fetch('/api/users').then(r => r.json()).then(setUsers)
}, [])

// ‚úÖ React Query (via Orval-generated hook or manual query)
const { data: users, isLoading, error } = useGetUsers()
```

---

## CUSTOM HOOKS

- Extract stateful logic into custom hooks to keep components clean
- A hook should do one thing
- Name hooks to describe what they return, not how they work: `useUserPermissions` not `useCheckAndFetchPermissions`
- Prefer hooks over HOCs and render props for composing behaviour

```ts
// ‚úÖ Encapsulate complexity in a hook
function useDisclosure(defaultOpen = false) {
  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(defaultOpen)
  const open = useCallback(() => setIsOpen(true), [])
  const close = useCallback(() => setIsOpen(false), [])
  const toggle = useCallback(() => setIsOpen(v => !v), [])
  return { isOpen, open, close, toggle }
}
```

